<cc:SdkSinglePageViewer
  Name    ="_1985cd45_f197_42d5_b75e_886add64b248"
  Tag     ="x:Key Attribute"
  xmlns:cc="clr-namespace:Microsoft.Windows.SdkViewer.Controls;assembly=SdkViewer"
  xmlns   ="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation">
  <FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation">
    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>x:Key Attribute</Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>Uniquely identifies elements that are intended to be referenced as resources, which exist within a ResourceDictionary.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>All child elements of a parent element that is a IDictionary implementation such as <Run FontWeight="Bold">ResourceDictionary</Run>
.must include an <Run FontWeight="Bold">x:Key</Run>
 attribute that specifies a unique key value within that dictionary. This is enforced at load time by the WPF XAML reader implementation. Missing and/or non-unique <Run FontWeight="Bold">x:Key</Run>
 values will result in load-time errors.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>Remarks</Run>

    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>The attribute value of <Run FontWeight="Bold">x:Key</Run>
 may be any string defined in the <Hyperlink NavigateUri="11e4cada-41d2-494d-9531-0d3df4dfcbe3.xaml">XAMLName Grammar</Hyperlink>
 or may be an object evaluated through a markup extension. For instance, the value of <Run FontWeight="Bold">x:Key</Run>
 may be a Type referenced by <Hyperlink NavigateUri="e0e0ce6f-e873-49c7-8ad7-8b840eb353ec.xaml">x:Type Markup Extension</Hyperlink>
. This type usage is most common in styles, where the <Run FontWeight="Bold">x:Key</Run>
 will be identical to the TargetType because that is the default style determination behavior whenever styling applies to elements through theming.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>Note that in the example below the <Run FontWeight="Bold">ResourceDictionary</Run>
 is implicit in how the XAML reader produces a collection to populate a Resources collection, and isn't typically provided explicitly as an element in markup, although it can be if desired for clarity (it would be a collection object element between the <Run FontWeight="Bold">Resources</Run>
 property element and the items within that populate the dictionary).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>In the WPF XAML reader implementation, the handling for this markup extension is typically defined by the ResourceKey class, in abstract form. However the reader produces different underlying extension types for keys in certain cases. For instance, the key for a DataTemplate or derived classes is handled separately and produces a distinct DataTemplateKey object.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>Example Attribute Usage</Run>

    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>
&lt;<Run FontStyle="italic">object</Run>
.Resources>
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>
&lt;<Run FontStyle="italic">object</Run>
<Run FontWeight="Bold">x:Key</Run>
="<Run FontStyle="italic">aStringKeyValue</Run>
".../>
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>
&lt;/<Run FontStyle="italic">object</Run>
.Resources>
    </Paragraph>

